    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">Imported From</rdfs:label>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:nodeID="N074920851e0946f2b0eead43f14abafa">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
    <owl:intersectionOf rdf:nodeID="N94edd5f30b0c4257b41b60c04fb46aeb"/>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/qualities/Qualities-Chemical/Lypophilic">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
    <rdfs:isDefinedBy rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/qualities/Qualities-Chemical/"/>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/qualities/Qualities-Chemical/ChemicalRelationalQuality"/>
    <rdfs:subClassOf>
      <owl:Restriction>
        <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/BFO_0000169"/>
        <owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/CHEBI_18059"/>
      </owl:Restriction>
    </rdfs:subClassOf>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="de">fettliebend</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">lypophilic</rdfs:label>
    <iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">lypophilic quality inheres in a bearer due to disposition toward affinity for fats, oils, lipids, and non-polar solvents, promoting dissolution and mixing</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
    <iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="de">Aufgrund der Affinität zu Fetten, Ölen, Lipiden und unpolaren Lösungsmitteln liegt einem Träger eine lipophile Qualität inne, die die Auflösung und Vermischung fördert</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
    <iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
    <iof-av:primitiveRationale xml:lang="en-US">Necessary and sufficient conditions for 'lypophilic' have not yet been formalized. The term is defined as a specific subtype of 'chemical relational quality'. Distinguishing criteria are domain-specific and depend on measurement conventions or source terminology not yet expressed as OWL restrictions.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
    <iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom xml:lang="en-US">ChemicalRelationalQuality(x) ← Lypophilic(x)</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
    <iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom xml:lang="en-US">if x is a &apos;lypophilic&apos; then x is a &apos;chemical relational quality&apos;</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
    <skos:example xml:lang="en-US">cholesterol is lypophilic, readily dissolving in lipid bilayers of cell membranes</skos:example>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/qualities/Qualities-Chemical/Hydrophilicity">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
    <rdfs:isDefinedBy rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/qualities/Qualities-Chemical/"/>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/qualities/Qualities-Chemical/ChemicalCapability"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="de">Hydrophilität</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">hydrophilicity</rdfs:label>
    <iof-av:adaptedFrom rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PATO_0002455"/>
    <iof-av:explanatoryNote>Hydrophilic molecule or portion of a molecule is one whose interactions with water and other polar substances are more thermodynamically favorable than their interactions with oil or other hydrophobic solvents. Typically charge-polarized and capable of hydrogen bonding, making them soluble not only in water but also in other polar solvents

Hydrophilic molecules (and portions of molecules) contrast with hydrophobic molecules (and portions of molecules). In some cases, both hydrophilic and hydrophobic properties occur in a single molecule. An example is the lipids that comprise the cell membrane. Another example is soap, which has a hydrophilic head and a hydrophobic tail, allowing it to dissolve in both water and oil

Hydrophilic and hydrophobic molecules are also known as polar molecules and nonpolar molecules, respectively. Some hydrophilic substances do not dissolve; this type of mixture is called a colloid</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
    <iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">hydrophilicity is a disposition enabling an entity to absorb or dissolve in water, characterized by charge polarization and hydrogen bonding</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
    <iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="de">Hydrophilie ist eine Eigenschaft, die es einer Substanz ermöglicht, Wasser zu absorbieren oder darin aufzulösen, gekennzeichnet durch Ladungspolarisation und Wasserstoffbrückenbindung</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
    <iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
    <iof-av:primitiveRationale xml:lang="en-US">Necessary and sufficient conditions for 'hydrophilicity' have not yet been formalized. The term is defined as a specific subtype of 'chemical capability'. Distinguishing criteria are domain-specific and depend on measurement conventions or source terminology not yet expressed as OWL restrictions. The definition is adapted from: http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PATO_0002455.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
    <iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom xml:lang="en-US">ChemicalCapability(x) ← Hydrophilicity(x)</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
    <iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom xml:lang="en-US">if x is a &apos;hydrophilicity&apos; then x is a &apos;chemical capability&apos;</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
    <skos:example xml:lang="en-US">the hydrophilicity of polyethylene glycol enables its use as a water-soluble polymer in pharmaceutical coatings</skos:example>
  </rdf:Description>
